week 1 
Internet
A global network of interconnected computers that communicate using the TCP/IP protocol.

IP Address
A unique address assigned to every device on a network for identification and communication.
Example:
192.168.1.10


Public IP
An IP address that is accessible over the Internet.
Example:
54.247.22.225

Private IP
An IP address used inside a private network and not directly accessible from the Internet.
Example:
172.31.34.52

DNS (Domain Name System)
Converts domain names into IP addresses.
Example:
google.com
      ↓
142.250.xxx.xxx

Router
A networking device that connects different networks and forwards data using IP addresses.

Switch
A networking device that connects devices within the same LAN using MAC addresses.

Firewall
A security system that filters incoming and outgoing network traffic based on predefined rules.

SSH (Secure Shell)
A secure protocol used to remotely access and manage Linux servers.
Example:
ssh -i key.pem ubuntu@54.247.xxx.xxx

Packet
A small unit of data transmitted over a network.

Port
A logical communication endpoint used by applications.
Common Ports:
Port	Service
22	SSH
80	HTTP
443	HTTPS
3306	MySQL

TCP
A reliable, connection-oriented protocol.

UDP
A fast, connectionless protocol.

OSI Model
A 7-layer reference model describing how data travels across a network.
Layers:
Physical
Data Link
Network
Transport
Session
Presentation
Application

TCP/IP Model
A practical 4-layer networking model used on the Internet.
